Python `.pyc` Files – Quick Notes

• Python creates `.pyc` files automatically when a `.py` file is executed or imported
• These files are stored inside the `__pycache__` folder

Why `.pyc` files are created:
• To speed up program execution
• Python compiles source code into bytecode once and reuses it

Why only one file got a `.pyc`:
• Only files that are actually run or imported get compiled
• Example: if `converters.py` is imported, it gets a `.pyc` file
• Files not used (like `inheritance.py`) won’t have `.pyc` yet

Filename meaning:
• `converters.cpython-314.pyc`

* `converters` → original file name
* `cpython-314` → Python version (3.14)
* `.pyc` → compiled bytecode

Important points:
• Safe to delete anytime
• Python will recreate them automatically
• Usually not added to Git

Git ignore:
**pycache**/
*.pyc


Source Root (Python)

• A source root is the main folder where Python starts searching for modules
• It is added to Python’s import path

Why it is used:
• Makes imports work correctly
• Prevents ModuleNotFoundError
• Keeps project organized

Example:
• If "Python/" is source root:
from Day_6.listes import numbers  ✅ works

• Without source root:
Import may fail ❌

In PyCharm:
• Right click folder → Mark Directory as → Sources Root


